observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. require the Inventory Committee created under AO No. OMH-3-2024, to conduct a comprehensive physical count and inspection of all PPE items to fully verify their existence and condition and to incorporate the results into the prescribed format of RPCPPE;
b. instruct the Municipal Accounting Office and the MGSO to address any deficiencies that may arise out of the conduct of complete inventory-taking of all PPE items, and update and maintain the required PCs/ PLCs in their custody, including the maintenance of RPLCs for land, for easy reference during the conduct of inventory-taking;
c. require the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustment/ reclassification for each item with cost below the capitalization threshold of P50,000.00 or those considered as semi-expendable property following COA Circular No. 2022-004; and
d. adopt and fully implement the one-time cleansing procedures of PPE accounts incorporated into the COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to properly address the missing/unaccounted/undocumented PPE items that have been in the books for several years, for a valid reporting and presentation of PPE accounts balances that are verifiable, accurate and in existence, thus, attain fairness of presentation of all PPE accounts in the Financial Statements of the Municipality at every reporting period.

a. require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and record the necessary adjusting entries to correct the noted misstatements and ensure the fair presentation of the Municipality’s financial statements;
b. direct the Municipal Budget Officer to provide the Municipal Accountant with the necessary balances related to the LDRRMF prior to the closing of the books, to ensure the proper identification of unexpended/unobligated balances; and
c. instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer all unexpended/unobligated QRF and DRRMF-MOOE balances to the Special Trust Fund under “Trust Liability–DRRM” before closing the books, and record necessary entries per accounting guidelines.

a. require the HRMO to submit the approved contracts or appointments of Job Order personnel for the 1st to 3rd quarters of CY 2024, supporting the payment totaling P6,515,964.35, to the Audit Team for verification;
b. require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all payments to JO personnel be supported with duly signed contracts or appointments specifying the nature of duties, rate of compensation, and duration of employment, to establish the validity and regularity of such payments; and
c. direct the Municipal Human Resource Management Office (HRMO) to establish and enforce standardized policies and procedures for the hiring and engagement of JO personnel, including the issuance of formal job descriptions and documentation of recruitment and approval processes.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. require accountable officers to liquidate cash advances within the prescribed period or before the end of each fiscal year, pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002, and to ensure that liquidation is supported with complete and proper documentation;
b. instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to maintain a systematic monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of cash advances, and to refrain from processing disbursement vouchers for new cash advances or granting simultaneous cash advances to any employee until all previous cash advances have been fully settled;
c. instruct the Municipal Accountant to issue a Certification confirming that previous cash advances have been liquidated and properly recorded in the books, and require that no disbursement vouchers for new cash advances be processed without this mandatory Certification.

8.5 We recommended and the Management agreed to submit for review the
following documents in order for the AT to arrive at an appropriate audit
action, viz:

a.1 Approved local development plan and public investment program;

a.2 Certificate of Net Debt Service Ceiling and Borrowing capacity
issued by the Bureau of Local Government Finance (BLGF);

a.3 Monetary Board Opinion from the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas to
determine the macroeconomic implications of the proposed
borrowing;

a.4 Certification of existing loan duly certified by the Local Treasurer;
and

a.5 Certification by the Lending Institution not requiring LGU deposits
as compensating balance for the loan.

We recommended and the LCE
agreed to require the
(a) General Services Officer to
(i) perform the duties and responsibilities mandated under Section 490 (b) of the Local Government Code RA 7160;
(ii) render report on the donations received by her Office;
(b) Municipal Accountant to
(i) record In-kind Donations received;
(ii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements of information pertaining to DRRM particularly on the quantity of donated relief goods received, issued and balance as well as the receipt of donated PPE (if any) and its disposal/transfer; and
(c) Committee on Physical Inventory of PPE to include those In-kind Donations received by the municipality in the physical count and render its corresponding Inventory Report.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. create an Inventory Committee for the Municipality for the conduct of complete detailed physical count of all the Municipality’s properties taking into provisions mandated under COA Circular 2020-006; and
b. instruct the Inventory Team required inventory reports stated on the above-mentioned regulations; 
c. order the Office of the General Service Officer (GSO)/ Municipal Treasurer to prepare property Acknowledgment Receipt for all PPEs; 
d. require the Municipal Accountant to work coordinately on all causes of discrepancies towards the reconciliation of their respective records to ascertain the accuracy of the PPE balances in the financial statements; and
e. require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the required ledger cards for all properties.

In view of the foregoing and in order to strengthen the controls in the handling of collections, we recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Verify the Report of Collections and Deposits, to review, check and monitor the issued official receipts as to series numbers, dates, total collections remitted and frequency of remittances by the different collectors as reflected in their prepared individual Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD) before recording and posting in the cashbook, pursuant to Section 64 of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, Volume 1 and Section 54 (a.2) of Government Accounting and Auditing Manual (GAAM) Vol. III;
b. Facilitate review, establish cash accountability and require the collectors to maintain a cash book and record transactions in a systematic and chronological order so that collection balances could be easily determined;
c. Provide explanation for undeposited collections and the unchecked practice of alterations and undating the official receipts and issuance thereof in non-chronological order.
We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct:
a. The collectors/personnel concerned to explain in writing why there are undated duplicate Official Receipts and erasures/alterations on the dates in the said duplicates;
b. The Municipal Accountant to provide an explanation regarding this matter;
Lastly, we recommended the Municipal Mayor to consider the re-shuffling of staff assigned to the Office of Municipal Treasurer.

We reiterated our recommendations that that the LCE direct all department heads and the designated Supply Officer to:

(a) formulate policies and procedures in the control and monitoring of all inventories purchased and received; 

(b) religiously conduct physical count of all inventories in order to establish the correct balances of the accounts and prepare and submit the required Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) resulting therefrom; 

(c) ensure the preparation and timely submission of reports pertaining to the issuance of inventory items; and 

(d) strictly comply with the rules and regulations contained in the NGAS Manual and COA Circular 2014-002 for the proper recording, valuation and preparation of the required inventory reports.

Further, we recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to instruct the personnel in-charge in the recording of inventories to:

(a) prepare and maintain the supplies ledger cards for all inventories; 

(b) properly analyze each transaction before recording in the books to ensure proper recognition and valuation of inventories in the books of account; and 

(c) make the necessary adjusting entries called for based on the foregoing deficiencies noted.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Local Finance Committee to come up with possible measures to avoid further incurrence of cash overdraft;
Prioritize the remittance of mandatory obligations to GSIS, Pag-Ibig and Philhealth to prevent incurrence of penalties and surcharges;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer that upon certification of availability of funds the equivalent amount should be set aside and not to be used for any other purpose;
Require the OIC-Accountant to review the composition of all payable accounts to determine their validity and effect promptly the necessary accounting entries to revert all undocumented payables; and
See to it that monies held in trust be used only for the intended purpose pursuant to Section 305(e) of RA 7160.
The Management was amenable to the observation and agreed to adhere to the audit recommendation.

We recommended that Management:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the purchases of supplies, goods and other items that qualify as part of inventory by debiting the appropriate inventory account;
recognize the remaining unused supplies, medicines and goods for distribution reported per office as well as donated items, under the appropriate inventory account;
to make an adjustment for the consumed supplies that are still included in the year-end inventory accounts;
require the GSO to prepare and submit monthly the SSMI together with the supporting RIS to the Accountant for the recognition of the expense; and
require the Inventory Committee to conduct comprehensive physical count of all types of inventories to give enough time to prepare the RPCI and submit the same on or before January 31 of the ensuing year.
The audit recommendation was well taken by the Management.

4.9 We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct comprehensive physical count earlier to give enough time to prepare the RPCPPE and submit the same on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to drop in the PPE accounts the reported items totaling ₱2,081,779.85 which did not qualify as PPE. Hence, ensure that all property and equipment recorded in the books qualify as PPE pursuant to Item 4.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record in the books the donated equipment from the Department of Health. Henceforth, remind the recipient office of donated assets, if any, to inform the GSO and Accounting office for proper recording in the books; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.
4.10 The Management agreed to the recommendation and promised to submit the RPCPPE once the reconciliation between with the GSO and Accounting records is finished.

