We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

submit an explanation/ justification on the noted observations/deviations on implemented projects; 
ensure that projects programmed for implementation are capital investments for implementation during the budget year rather than on “as needed basis” and also ensure that PPAs are aligned with the Philippine Development Plan, the Medium-Term Public Investment Program; 
require the Municipal Planning and Development Council and Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that the specific projects proposed for local funding are included in the Annual Budget in accordance with applicable laws; 
require the Municipal Engineer to (i) refer to DPWH DO. No. 52, series of 2012 for the necessary documents for civil works in case of temporary work suspension and Annex E of RA No. 9184 for the guidelines in the preparation and submission of Variation/Change/Extra Work Order; and (ii) check the progress of the construction at all reasonable times during the project implementation to ensure that there is no negative slippage; and
require the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that documents are complete before payment to contractor is made.

We recommended that management:

institute segregation of incompatible duties and responsibilities to prevent errors and fraud by ensuring that no single person has complete control over the assessment, collection and recording function;
instruct the designated staff in the releasing and recording of business permits to (i) use the original OR as basis in the recording of paid fees and charges, (ii) keep true copies of the original OR and issued Mayor’s Business Permits on file, and (iii) ensure that postings made in the logbook and permits are correct and accurate;
direct the designated BPLO/collecting officer to restitute the unreported collections amounting to ₱55,750.48; 
cause the immediate relief of the erring officer from duties and responsibilities as collecting officer and transfer her to a position where monetary accountability is not involved; and,
ensure that internal control policies on the assessment, receipt and collection of taxes, charges and fees for the application/renewal of business permits are strictly observed and implemented.

observations.managementAction:
In his letter dated November 22, 2018, the Local Chief Executive informed that, to address the lapses noted in the audit, the following were instituted:

The designation of a new Business Permit and Licensing Officer (BPLO);
Instructed the newly designated BPLO that the issuance of Official Receipt (OR) for Business Permit shall be done by the other collecting officer to ascertain check and balance in the assessment, collection and recording tasks;
Relieved the former BPLO from her duties and responsibilities as collecting officer;
The unremitted collections totaling ₱56,850.48 were settled by the former BPLO under OR No. 1015077 dated November 19, 2018;
Directed the staff at the Office of the Mayor who is in charge of issuing Business Permit to secure photocopies of Original OR and Mayor’s Business Permit Certificate for records purposes and for proper recoding in the logbook

