(iii) post in the PhilGEPS the RFQ and Award  on the procurements covered by small value procurements of more than ₱50,000.00 for three days, except for unforeseen contingency requiring immediate purchase, for information purposes;

(b)	BAC Secretariat and all the offices concerned to prepare a complete Annual Procurement Plan containing all the requirements of the Municipality, procurement schedule, and mode of procurement; 

(c)	 Supply Officer to submit all copies of contracts and purchase orders to the Audit Team within the prescribed period; and

(d)	Municipal Accountant to ensure that the necessary documents supporting payment claims are complete before payment is made to suppliers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

(a) issue a supplemental order to specifically identify the members of the Technical Working Group (TWG) of the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) pursuant to Rule VI, Section 37 of the Magna Carta of Women; 

(b) encourage and direct the GFPS to perform its mandated tasks and to strengthen the monitoring and evaluation system to assess the effectiveness and efficiency of their gender mainstreaming efforts; 

(c) where feasible, cause the establishment of a GAD Office or unit under the Office of the LCE that will support and coordinate all GAD-related PPAs and concerns of the LGU GFPS. The LCE may also appoint or designate the LGU personnel to manage the GAD office and/or unit; and

(d) direct the GFPS and its TWG  to:

(i) exert  efforts to come up with a database on sex-disaggregated data or perform gender analysis to ensure that allocation of funds on GAD-related PPAs to ensure is not based on incorrect assumption and stereotypes; 

(ii)  ensure that the allocated funds are maximized for the implementation of the GAD activities; 

(iii) conscientiously follow the prescribed template for the preparation of the GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) and GAD Accomplishment Report; and 

(iv) strictly comply with the pertinent provisions of issued guidelines on GAD particularly that of RA No. 9710 and PCW-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01.

We recommended that, for future similar undertakings, the Municipal Engineer in coordination with the  Head of the Bids and Awards Committee:

strictly adhere to the provisions of the above-cited regulation in reference to the required documentation for a particular transaction to protect the interest of the government and support the propriety of disbursements;

draw Pakyaw labor from the vicinity of the project, or pakyaw  labor groups belong to various Barangay Associations adjacent to the projects site and establish the proof of such;

appoint a Project Facilitator who shall assist in the organization of the Pakyaw Groups and preparation of the Pakyaw Contracts, organize community meetings pertinent to the project among others;

assign among the pakyaw labor groups a Group Leader who will represent the group and sign to documents in behalf of the group; and

prepare a Pakyaw contract which shall delineate the responsibilities of both parties, the skill category of each pakyaw group member, such as, skilled, semi-skilled, or unskilled and indicate their exact residences for easy future reference.

